Table.name: applicationRuntimeTable
Table.Description: An application represents a Java EE enterprise application packaged in an EAR file or EAR exploded directory. The EAR file or directory contains a set of components such as WAR, EJB, and RAR connector components, each of which can be deployed on one or more targets. A target is a server or a cluster. Modules in the application can have one of the following states: UNPREPARED - Indicates that none of the modules in this application are currently prepared or active. PREPARED - Indicates that none of the modules in this application are currently prepared or active. ACTIVATED - Indicates that at least one module in this application is currently active. ApplicationRuntimeMBean encapsulates runtime information about a deployed enterprise application.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeEntry
Object.Description: Entry of applicationRuntimeTable

Object.name: applicationRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

Object.name: applicationRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: JMX-standard MBean name

Object.name: applicationRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeParent
Object.Description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

Object.name: applicationRuntimeApplicationName
Object.Description: The name of the application.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeApplicationVersion
Object.Description: The application's version identifier. This is particularly useful, when using the side-by-side deployment feature, to differentiate between two different versions of the same application that are deployed at the same time.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeActiveVersionState
Object.Description: Specifies whether this application version is the currently active version. An application can be the only version currently deployed, or it can have more than one version currently deployed, using the side-by-side deployment feature. If more than one version is deployed, only one version can be active. This attribute specifies the state the current application version is in. An application can be in an INACTIVE state, which means that it has not been activated yet, or that there is more than one version of the application deployed (using side-by-side deployment) and this version is retiring. An application can be in ACTIVE_ADMIN state, which means that it is the currently active version for administrative channel requests. An application can be in ACTIVE state, which means that it is the currently active version for normal (non-administrative) channel requests.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeOverallHealthState
Object.Description: The overall health of the application including that of some of the components that report health. Currently, only connector modules report health status and are the only ones considered in the overall health state of the application.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeHealthState
Object.Description: The HealthState MBean for the application.

Object.name: applicationRuntimeInternal
Object.Description: Indicates whether this application is an internal application. Such applications are not displayed in the console or persisted in the config.xml.

Object.name: applicationRuntimePartitionName
Object.Description: The application's partition. Returns the partition to which this application is deployed.

Table.Description: This class is used for monitoring a server's view of the members of a WebLogic cluster within a WebLogic domain.

Object.Description: Entry of clusterRuntimeTable

Object.name: clusterRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

Object.name: clusterRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: JMX-standard MBean name

Object.name: clusterRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeParent
Object.Description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

Object.name: clusterRuntimeAliveServerCount
Object.Description: Provides the current total number of alive servers in this cluster. Returns the current total number of alive servers in this cluster.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeResendRequestsCount
Object.Description: Provides the number of state-delta messages that had to be resent because a receiving server in the cluster missed a message. Returns the number of state-delta messages that had to be resent because a receiving server in the cluster missed a message.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeFragmentsSentCount
Object.Description: Returns the total number of message fragments sent from this server into the cluster. This is applicable to both multicast and unicast message types.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeFragmentsReceivedCount
Object.Description: Provides the total number of messages received on this server from the cluster. This is applicable to both multicast and unicast message types.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeMulticastMessagesLostCount
Object.Description: Provides the total number of in-coming multicast messages that were lost according to this server.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeServerNames
Object.Description: Provides the names of the servers in the cluster.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeSecondaryDistributionNames
Object.Description: Provides the names of the remote servers (such as myserver) for which the local server is hosting secondary objects. The name is appended with a number to indicate the number of secondaries hosted on behalf of that server.

Object.name: clusterRuntimePrimaryCount
Object.Description: Provides the number of object that the local server hosts as primaries. Answer the number of object that the local server hosts as primaries.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeForeignFragmentsDroppedCount
Object.Description: Provides the number of fragments that originated in foreign domains or clusters which use the same multicast address. Answer the number of fragments that originated in foreign domains/cluster that use the same multicast address.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeDetailedSecondariesDistribution
Object.Description: Provides the names of the remote servers (such as myserver) for which the local server is hosting secondary objects. The name is appended with a number to indicate the number of secondaries hosted on behalf of that server.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeActiveSingletonServices
Object.Description: Returns an array of the names of the singleton services that are active on this server.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeSecondaryCount
Object.Description: Answer the number of object that the local server hosts as secondaries.

Object.name: clusterRuntimeHealthState
Object.Description: Provides health information returned by the server self-health monitor service. HEALTH_OK = 0, Server service is healthy. HEALTH_WARN = 1, Service could have problems in the future. Check the server logs and the corresponding RuntimeMBean for more details. HEALTH_CRITICAL = 2, Something must be done now to prevent service failure. Check the server logs and the corresponding RuntimeMBean for more details. HEALTH_FAILED = 3, Service has failed - must be restarted. Check the server logs and the corresponding RuntimeMBean for more details. HEALTH_OVERLOADED = 4, Service is functioning normally but there is too much work in it. CRITICAL and OVERLOADED are different. A subsystem is in the critical state when a part of it is malfunctioning, for example, stuck threads. An overloaded state means that there is more work assigned to the service than the configured threshold. A service might refuse more work in this state. LOW_MEMORY_REASON = 'server is low on memory', Reason code that indicates that the server is low on memory. Administrators can configure low and high thresholds for memory usage. The server health changes to OVERLOADED with this reason code if the low threshold is reached.

Table.name: queryCacheRuntimeTable
Table.Description: This interface contains accessor methods for all query cache runtime information collected for an EJB. The cache miss counts need some explaining. A query-cache miss can occur due to one of the following reasons: The query result was not found in the query-cache The query result has timed out A bean which satisfies the query wasnot found in the entity cache A query with relationship-caching turned on did not find the related-beans query result A query which loads multiple EJBs could not load one or more of them To better aid tuning, there are separate counters provided for each of the last four of the above causes. The fifth counter is a total cache miss counter. This counter takes into account all five causes of a cache miss.

Object.Description: Provides a count of the total number of query results for this EJB currently in the query cache. Returns the total number of query results for this EJB currently in the EJB cache.

Object.name: queryCacheRuntimeCacheAccessCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the number of accesses of the query cache for this EJB. Returns the number of accesses of the query cache for this EJB.

Object.name: queryCacheRuntimeCacheHitCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the number of cache hits of the query cache for this EJB. Returns the number of cache hits of the query cache for this EJB.

Object.name: queryCacheRuntimeTotalCacheMissCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the total number of cache misses of the query cache for this EJB. Returns the total number of cache misses of the query cache for this EJB.

Object.name: queryCacheRuntimeCacheMissByTimeoutCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the number of cache misses of the query cache for this EJB due to query results timing out. Returns the number of cache misses due to query result timeout for this EJB.

Object.name: queryCacheRuntimeCacheMissByBeanEvictionCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the number of cache misses of the query cache for this EJB because corresponding beans were not found in the entity cache. Returns the number of times a cache miss occurred for this EJB because corresponding beans were not found in the entity cache.

Object.name: queryCacheRuntimeCacheMissByRelatedQueryMissCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the number of cache misses of the query cache for this EJB because a related query was not found in another EJB's query cache. Returns the number of times a cache miss occurred for this EJB because a related query was not found in another EJB's query cache.

Object.name: queryCacheRuntimeCacheMissByDependentQueryMissCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the number of cache misses of the query cache for this EJB because a dependent query was not found in another EJB's query cache. Returns the number of times a cache miss occurred for this EJB because a dependent query was not found in another EJB's query cache.

Table.Description: This interface contains accessor methods for all cache runtime information collected for an EJB. Note that the sum of the cacheHitCount and cacheMissCount may not add up to the cacheAccessCount in a running server because these metrics are retrieved using multiple calls and the counts could change between the calls.

Object.name: ejbCacheRuntimeCacheAccessCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the total number of attempts to access a bean from the cache. The sum of the Cache Hit Count and Cache Miss Count may not add up to the cacheAccessCount in a running server because these metrics are retrieved using multiple calls and the counts could change between the calls.*

The sum of the Cache Hit Count and Cache Miss Count may not add up to the cacheAccessCount in a running server because these metrics are retrieved using multiple calls and the counts could change between the calls.

Object.name: ejbCacheRuntimePassivationCount
Object.Description: Provides a count of the total number of beans from this EJB Home that have been passivated.

Object.name: ejbCacheRuntimeCacheMissCount

The sum of the Cache Hit Count and Cache Miss Count may not add up to the cacheAccessCount in a running server because these metrics are retrieved using multiple calls and the counts could change between the calls.

Object.Description: Generated Object.

Object.Description: Returns the current capacity of this connection pool.

Object.Description: Number of cases when a connection pool attempted to refresh a connection to a database and failed

Object.Description: Returns the highest number of available connections in this pool

Object.name: jdbcConnectionPoolRuntimeHighestNumUnavailable
Object.Description: Returns the highest number of unavailable connections in this pool

Object.Description: Number of leaked connections.

Object.name: jdbcConnectionPoolRuntimeNumAvailable

Object.name: jdbcConnectionPoolRuntimeNumUnavailable
Object.Description: Returns the number of unavailable connections in this pool

Object.name: jdbcConnectionPoolRuntimeStatementProfileCount
Object.Description: Number of the SQL statement profiles in profile storage.

Object.name: jdbcConnectionPoolRuntimeModuleId
Object.Description: Returns the identifier for this Component. The identifier is unique within the application. Typical modules will use the URI for their id. Web Modules will return their context-root since the web-uri may not be unique within an EAR.

Object.name: jdbcConnectionPoolRuntimeState
Object.Description: The current state of the connection pool. Possible values are: Running if the pool is enabled (deployed and not Suspended). This is the normal state of the connection pool. Suspended if the pool disabled. Shutdown if the pool is shutdown and all database connections have been closed. Unknown if the pool state is unknown. Unhealthy if all connections are unavailable (not because they are in use). This state occurs if the database server is unavailable when the connection pool is created (creation retry must be enabled) or if all connections have failed connection tests (on creation, on reserve, on release, or periodic testing).

Object.name: jdbcConnectionPoolRuntimeDeploymentState
Object.Description: The current deployment state of the module. A module can be in one and only one of the following states. State can be changed via deployment or administrator console. - UNPREPARED. State indicating at this module is neither prepared or active. - PREPARED. State indicating at this module of this application is prepared, but not active. The classes have been loaded and the module has been validated. - ACTIVATED. State indicating at this module is currently active. - NEW. State indicating this module has just been created and is being initialized.

Table.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeTable
Table.Description: This class is used for monitoring a WebLogic JDBC Data Source and its associated connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeEntry
Object.Description: Entry of jdbcDataSourceRuntimeTable

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: JMX-standard MBean name

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeParent
Object.Description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeLeakedConnectionCount
Object.Description: The number of leaked connections. A leaked connection is a connection that was reserved from the data source but was not returned to the data source by calling close().

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeEnabled
Object.Description: Indicates whether the data source is enabled or disabled: true if the data source is enabled. false if the data source is disabled.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeState
Object.Description: The current state of the data source. Possible states are: Running - the data source is enabled (deployed and not Suspended). This is the normal state of the data source. This state includes conditions when the database server is not available and the data source is created (creation retry must be enabled) or when all connections have failed connection tests (on creation, on reserve, or periodic testing). Suspended - the data source has been disabled. Shutdown - the data source is shutdown and all database connections have been closed. Overloaded - all resources in pool are in use. Unknown - the data source state is unknown.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeFailuresToReconnectCount
Object.Description: The number of times that the data source attempted to refresh a database connection and failed. Failures may occur when the database is unavailable or when the network connection to the database is interrupted.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeConnectionDelayTime
Object.Description: The average amount of time, in milliseconds, that it takes to create a physical connection to the database. The value is calculated as summary of all times to connect divided by the total number of connections.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheAccessCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of times that the statement cache was accessed.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheAddCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of statements added to the statement cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements added to the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheDeleteCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of statements discarded from the cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements that were discarded from the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheCurrentSize
Object.Description: The number of prepared and callable statements currently cached in the statement cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements in the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheHitCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of times that statements from the cache were used.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheMissCount
Object.Description: The number of times that a statement request could not be satisfied with a statement from the cache.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsCurrentCount
Object.Description: The number of connections currently in use by applications.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionCurrentCount
Object.Description: The number of connection requests waiting for a database connection.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeVersionJDBCDriver
Object.Description: The driver class name of the JDBC driver used to create database connections.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of active database connections in this instance of the data source since the data source was instantiated. Active connections are connections in use by an application.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsAverageCount
Object.Description: Average number of active connections in this instance of the data source. Active connections are connections in use by an application. This value is only valid if the resource is configured to allow shrinking.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeReserveRequestCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeFailedReserveRequestCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that could not be fulfilled.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of application requests concurrently waiting for a connection from this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection, including those that eventually got a connection and those that did not get a connection.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionSuccessTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection and eventually succeeded in getting a connection.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionFailureTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection and eventually failed to get a connection. Waiting connection requests can fail for a variety of reasons, including waiting for longer than the ConnectionReserveTimeoutSeconds.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeWaitSecondsHighCount
Object.Description: The highest number of seconds that an application waited for a connection (the longest connection reserve wait time) from this instance of the connection pool since the connection pool was instantiated. This value is updated when a completed getConnection request takes longer to return a connection than any previous request.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeConnectionsTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of database connections created in this data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeCurrCapacity
Object.Description: The current count of JDBC connections in the connection pool in the data source.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeCurrCapacityHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections available or in use (current capacity) in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeNumAvailable
Object.Description: The number of database connections that are currently idle and available to be used by applications in this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeHighestNumAvailable
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections that were idle and available to be used by an application at any time in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeNumUnavailable
Object.Description: The number of connections currently in use by applications or being tested in this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeHighestNumUnavailable
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections that were in use by applications or being tested by the system in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeModuleId
Object.Description: Returns the identifier for this Component. The identifier is unique within the application. Typical modules will use the URI for their id. Web Modules will return their context-root since the web-uri may not be unique within an EAR.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeDeploymentState
Object.Description: The current deployment state of the module. A module can be in one and only one of the following states. State can be changed via deployment or administrator console. UNPREPARED. State indicating at this module is neither prepared or active. PREPARED. State indicating at this module of this application is prepared, but not active. The classes have been loaded and the module has been validated. ACTIVATED. State indicating at this module is currently active. NEW. State indicating this module has just been created and is being initialized.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeDatabaseProductName
Object.Description: The product name of the database that this data source is connected to.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeDriverVersion
Object.Description: The version of the JDBC driver that this data source is configured to use.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeDriverName
Object.Description: The product name of the JDBC driver that this data source is configured to use.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeDatabaseProductVersion
Object.Description: The product version of the database that this data source is connected to.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeRepurposeCount
Object.Description: The number of times connections have been repurposed since the datasource was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeUnresolvedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes unsuccessfully resolved in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeResolvedAsCommittedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes successfully resolved as committed in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeCommitOutcomeRetryTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcome query retries conducted before resolving the outcome or exceeding the retry seconds in this data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeResolvedAsNotCommittedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes successfully resolved as not committed in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcDataSourceRuntimeFailedRepurposeCount
Object.Description: The number of repurpose errors that have occurred since the datasource was deployed.

Table.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeTable
Table.Description: This class is used for monitoring pooled JMS connections. A pooled JMS connection is a session pool used by EJBs and servlets that use a resource-reference element in their EJB or Servlet deployment descriptor to define their JMS connection factories.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeEntry
Object.Description: Entry of jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeTable

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: JMX-standard MBean name

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeParent
Object.Description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeAverageReserved
Object.Description: The average number of JMS sessions that have been in use in this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated. This generally happens when an EJB or servlet is deployed that requires the session pool.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeCreationDelayTime
Object.Description: The average amount of time that it takes to create each JMS session in the session pool.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeCurrCapacity
Object.Description: The current capacity of the session pool, which is always less than or equal to the maximum capacity of JMS sessions.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeHighestNumAvailable
Object.Description: The highest number of available JMS sessions in this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeHighestNumReserved
Object.Description: The highest number of concurrent JMS sessions reserved for this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeNumAvailable
Object.Description: The number of available JMS sessions in the session pool that are not currently in use.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeHighestNumWaiters
Object.Description: The highest number of threads waiting to retrieve a JMS session in this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeHighestWaitSeconds
Object.Description: The highest number of seconds that an application waited to retrieve a JMS session in this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeMaxCapacity
Object.Description: The maximum number of JMS sessions that can be allocated using the session pool.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeNumConnectionObjects
Object.Description: The number of JMS connections that back this session pool. This value may be greater than one if different sessions were created using different combinations of a username and password to contact the JMS server.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeNumFailuresToRefresh
Object.Description: The number of failed attempts to create a JMS session in the session pool.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeNumLeaked
Object.Description: The number of JMS sessions that were removed from the session pool, but were not returned.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeNumReserved
Object.Description: The number of JMS sessions that are currently in use.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeNumUnavailable
Object.Description: The number of JMS sessions in the session pool that are not currently usable for some reason.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeNumWaiters
Object.Description: The number of threads waiting to retrieve a JMS session from the session pool.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeTotalNumAllocated
Object.Description: The total number of JMS sessions allocated by this session pool in this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeTotalNumDestroyed
Object.Description: The total number of JMS sessions that were created and then destroyed in this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated.

Object.name: jmsPooledConnectionRuntimeHighestNumUnavailable
Object.Description: The highest number of unusable JMS sessions in this instance of the session pool since it was instantiated.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimeMessagesPagedOutTotalCount
Object.Description: Return the total number of messages that were written to the paging directory since the JMS server was started.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimeInsertionPausedState
Object.Description: Returns the current insertion paused state of the JMSServer as string value.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimeMessagesPageableCurrentCount
Object.Description: Return the number of messages that are currently available for paging in this JMS server but have not yet been paged out. Note that due to internal implementation details, this count may be zero even if 'PageableByteCurrentCount' is zero.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimeProductionPausedState
Object.Description: Returns the current production paused state of the JMSServer as string value.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimeBytesPagedOutTotalCount
Object.Description: Return the total number of bytes that were written to the paging directory since the JMS server was started.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimeBytesPagedInTotalCount
Object.Description: Return the total number of bytes that were read from the paging directory since the JMS server was started.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimeTransactions
Object.Description: Returns an array of Xids representing transaction branches that exist on this JMS server in any state.

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimePendingTransactions
Object.Description: Returns an array of Xids representing transaction branches that exist onthis JMS server in the pending state, i.e. branches that have been prepared by the transaction manager but not yet committed or rolled back.

Object.Description: See PersistentStoreRuntimeMBean.AllocatedWindowBufferBytes

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimePagingPhysicalWriteCount
Object.Description: See PersistentStoreRuntimeMBean.PhysicalWriteCount

Object.name: jmsServerRuntimePagingAllocatedIoBufferBytes
Object.Description: See PersistentStoreRuntimeMBean.AllocatedIoBufferBytes

Object.Description: The current deployment state of the module. A module can be in one and only one of the following states. State can be changed via deployment or administrator console. UNPREPARED. State indicating this module has just been created and is being initialized.

Table.name: jvmRuntimeTable

You cannot change the JVM's operating parameters while the JVM is active. Instead, use the startup options that are described in the JVM's documentation. The WebLogic JVM contains only one of these Runtime MBeans: If the JVM is an instance of a JRockit JDK, then the JVM contains JRockitRuntime MBean. Otherwise, it contains the JVMRuntimeMBean.

Object.Description: Indicates whether the port that the server uses for administrative traffic is configured to use a secure protocol.

Object.Description: Indicates whether the default SSL listen port is enabled on the server

Object.Description: The URL that the server and its clients use for administrative connections. If no administration channel is enabled, then this method returns the URL for connections through the default channel. If the default channel is de-activated, this method returns the URL for a secure channel. If no secure channel is enabled, the method returns null. The returned URL will be consistent with dynamic channel updates.

Object.name: serverRuntimeDefaultURL
Object.Description: The URL that clients use to connect to this server's default network channel. The returned value indicates the default protocol, listen address and listen port: protocol://listen-address:listen-port Note: The default protocol, listen address and listen port are persisted in the domain's config.xml file, however when a server instance is started, command-line options can override these persisted values. This getDefaultURL method returns the URL values that are currently being used, not necessarily the values that are specified in config.xml. The returned URL will be consistent with dynamic channel updates.

Object.name: serverRuntimeCurrentDirectory

Object.name: serverRuntimeWeblogicHome
Object.Description: The directory where the WebLogic Server instance (server) is installed, without the trailing '/server'.

Object.name: serverRuntimeMiddlewareHome
Object.Description: The Oracle Middleware installation directory.

Object.name: serverRuntimeOverallHealthState

Object.name: serverRuntimeHealthState
Object.Description: The health state of the server as reported by the server's self-health monitoring. For example, the server can report if it is overloaded by too many requests, if it needs more memory resources, or if it will soon fail for other reasons.

Object.name: serverRuntimePatchList
Object.Description: Returns information about installed patches on the server as an array of Strings. Each element of the array describes a patch, which is of the form: BugNumber;PatchID;DateApplied;Description

Object.name: serverRuntimeInSitConfigState
Object.Description: Returns true if sitconfig is applied.

This class is instantiated only on the Administration Server, but you can use it to transition the states of Managed Servers as well as Administration Servers. You cannot use it to start an Administration Server, and if you want to use it to start Managed Servers, you must first set up a Node Manager on each Managed Server's host machine. If you want to use the methods that transition a server into the ADMIN state, you must first set up an administration channel for that server.

Table.name: threadPoolRuntimeTable
Table.Description: This bean is used to monitor the self-tuning queue

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeEntry
Object.Description: Entry of threadPoolRuntimeTable

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: JMX-standard MBean name

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeParent
Object.Description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeExecuteThreadTotalCount
Object.Description: The total number of threads in the pool.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeExecuteThreadIdleCount
Object.Description: The number of idle threads in the pool. This count does not include standby threads and stuck threads. The count indicates threads that are ready to pick up new work when it arrives

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeQueueLength
Object.Description: The number of pending requests in the priority queue. This is the total of internal system requests and user requests.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimePendingUserRequestCount
Object.Description: The number of pending user requests in the priority queue. The priority queue contains requests from internal subsystems and users. This is just the count of all user requests.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeSharedCapacityForWorkManagers
Object.Description: Maximum amount of requests that can be accepted in the priority queue. Note that a request with higher priority will be accepted in place of a lower priority request already in the queue even after the threshold is reached. The lower priority request is kept waiting in the queue till all high priority requests are executed. Also note that further enqueues of the low priority requests are rejected right away.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeCompletedRequestCount
Object.Description: The number of completed requests in the priority queue.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeHoggingThreadCount
Object.Description: The threads that are being held by a request right now. These threads will either be declared as stuck after the configured timeout or will return to the pool before that. The self-tuning mechanism will backfill if necessary.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeStandbyThreadCount
Object.Description: The number of threads in the standby pool. Threads that are not needed to handle the present work load are designated as standby and added to the standby pool. These threads are activated when more threads are needed.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeThroughput
Object.Description: The mean number of requests completed per second.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeMinThreadsConstraintsPending
Object.Description: Number of requests that should be executed now to satisfy the min threads requirement.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeMinThreadsConstraintsCompleted
Object.Description: Number of requests with min threads constraint picked up out of order for execution immediately since their min threads requirement was not met. This does not include the case where threads are idle during schedule.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeSuspended
Object.Description: Indicates if the RequestManager is suspended. A suspended manager will not dequeue work and dispatch threads till it is resumed.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeStuckThreadCount
Object.Description: Number of stuck threads in the thread pool.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeOverloadRejectedRequestsCount
Object.Description: Number of requests rejected due to configured Shared Capacity for work managers have been reached.

Object.name: threadPoolRuntimeHealthState
Object.Description: The health state of this pool.

Table.name: taskRuntimeTable
Table.Description: Exposes monitoring information about an ongoing and potentially long-running administrative process. This should be taken to mean, at minimum, any OA&M operation involving I/O. Examples include starting and stopping servers, deploying and undeploying applications, or migrating services. An MBean operation of this sort should fork a separate thread to perform the actual work and immediately return an instance of TaskRuntimeMBean to the caller. The caller can then use this to track the task's progress as desired. Users can also query for all instances of TaskRuntimeMBean to get a summary of both currently-running and recently-completed tasks. Instance of TaskRuntimeMBean continue to exist in the MBeanServer after the completion of the work they describe. They will eventually either be explicitly deregistered by the user, or removed by a scavenger process which periodically purges instances of TaskRuntimeMBean that have been completed for some time.

Table.name: connectorComponentRuntimeTable
Table.Description: Generates notifications about the deployment state of resource adapters. (Each resource adapter is represented by an instance of {@link weblogic.management.configuration.ConnectorComponentMBean}.) In 2-phase deployment, if a resource adapter's state is PREPARED then it has achieved the first phase of deployment (everything is set up and all that remains is to enable a reference to the adapter). When the resource adapter is in an ACTIVATED state, it has achieved the second phase of deployment, in which applications can obtain a reference to the adapter. A server instance creates an instance of this interface when it creates an instance of weblogic.management.configuration.ConnectorComponentMBean.

The returned value is a standard java absolute time, which is measured in milliseconds since midnight, January 1, 1970 UTC This returns the JMS durable subscription boot time if there were no messages that were successfully delivered to any subscriber on this subscription since the subscription was booted. We define the boot time of a durable subscription to be the time the subscription is originally created or recovered during a server reboot or jms migration, which ever is latest.

Object.name: jMSDurableSubscriberRuntimeSubscriptionLimitDeletedCount

In addition, the interface provides access to sampling and snapshot statistics. All statistics are base on data collected during the current server session.

Object.Description: The number of times within this server session that the sampling time differed significantly enough from the average to be considered a statistical outlier. The Harvester removes these values form the ongoing averages.
