Table.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeTable
Table.Description: Runtime MBean that represents a Abstract JDBC data source.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeEntry
Object.Description: Generated SNMP Table Entry.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Index column

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeDatabaseProductName
Object.Description: The product name of the database that this data source is connected to.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheAccessCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of times that the statement cache was accessed.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeConnectionsTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of database connections created in this data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeDriverName
Object.Description: The product name of the JDBC driver that this data source is configured to use.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeHighestNumUnavailable
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections that were in use by applications or being tested by the system in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeDatabaseProductVersion
Object.Description: The product version of the database that this data source is connected to.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeHighestNumAvailable
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections that were idle and available to be used by an application at any time in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeWaitSecondsHighCount
Object.Description: The highest number of seconds that an application waited for a connection (the longest connection reserve wait time) from this instance of the connection pool since the connection pool was instantiated. This value is updated when a completed getConnection request takes longer to return a connection than any previous request.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of application requests concurrently waiting for a connection from this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeVersionJDBCDriver
Object.Description: The driver class name of the JDBC driver used to create database connections.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection, including those that eventually got a connection and those that did not get a connection.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeCurrCapacityHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections available or in use (current capacity) in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeModuleId
Object.Description: Returns the identifier for this Component. The identifier is unique within the application. Typical modules will use the URI for their id. Web Modules will return their context-root since the web-uri may not be unique within an EAR.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeNumUnavailable
Object.Description: The number of connections currently in use by applications or being tested in this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheHitCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of times that statements from the cache were used.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeFailedReserveRequestCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that could not be fulfilled.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionCurrentCount
Object.Description: The number of connection requests waiting for a database connection.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeConnectionDelayTime
Object.Description: The average amount of time, in milliseconds, that it takes to create a physical connection to the database. The value is calculated as summary of all times to connect divided by the total number of connections.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionFailureTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection and eventually failed to get a connection. Waiting connection requests can fail for a variety of reasons, including waiting for longer than the ConnectionReserveTimeoutSeconds.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeNumAvailable
Object.Description: The number of database connections that are currently idle and available to be used by applications in this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheAddCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of statements added to the statement cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements added to the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsAverageCount
Object.Description: Average number of active connections in this instance of the data source. Active connections are connections in use by an application. This value is only valid if the resource is configured to allow shrinking.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeLeakedConnectionCount
Object.Description: The number of leaked connections. A leaked connection is a connection that was reserved from the data source but was not returned to the data source by calling close().

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeDeploymentState
Object.Description: The current deployment state of the module. A module can be in one and only one of the following states. State can be changed via deployment or administrator console. UNPREPARED. State indicating at this module is neither prepared or active. PREPARED. State indicating at this module of this application is prepared, but not active. The classes have been loaded and the module has been validated. ACTIVATED. State indicating at this module is currently active. NEW. State indicating this module has just been created and is being initialized.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheCurrentSize
Object.Description: The number of prepared and callable statements currently cached in the statement cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements in the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsCurrentCount
Object.Description: The number of connections currently in use by applications.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeEnabled
Object.Description: Indicates whether the data source is enabled or disabled: true if the data source is enabled. false if the data source is disabled.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of active database connections in this instance of the data source since the data source was instantiated. Active connections are connections in use by an application.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeCurrCapacity
Object.Description: The current count of JDBC connections in the connection pool in the data source.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeFailuresToReconnectCount
Object.Description: The number of times that the data source attempted to refresh a database connection and failed. Failures may occur when the database is unavailable or when the network connection to the database is interrupted.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionSuccessTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection and eventually succeeded in getting a connection.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeDriverVersion
Object.Description: The version of the JDBC driver that this data source is configured to use.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeState
Object.Description: The current state of the data source. Possible states are: Running - the data source is enabled (deployed and not Suspended). This is the normal state of the data source. This state includes conditions when the database server is not available and the data source is created (creation retry must be enabled) or when all connections have failed connection tests (on creation, on reserve, or periodic testing). Suspended - the data source has been disabled. Shutdown - the data source is shutdown and all database connections have been closed. Overloaded - all resources in pool are in use. Unknown - the data source state is unknown.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeReserveRequestCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheMissCount
Object.Description: The number of times that a statement request could not be satisfied with a statement from the cache.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheDeleteCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of statements discarded from the cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements that were discarded from the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeRepurposeCount
Object.Description: The number of times connections have been repurposed since the datasource was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeUnresolvedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes unsuccessfully resolved in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeResolvedAsCommittedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes successfully resolved as committed in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeCommitOutcomeRetryTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcome query retries conducted before resolving the outcome or exceeding the retry seconds in this data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeResolvedAsNotCommittedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes successfully resolved as not committed in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcAbstractDataSourceRuntimeFailedRepurposeCount
Object.Description: The number of repurpose errors that have occurred since the datasource was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeFailedReplayCount
Object.Description: Obtains the number of replays that failed. When replay fails, it rethrows the original SQLRecoverableException to the application, with the reason for the failure chained to that original exception. Application can call getNextException to retrieve the reason.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeTotalRequests
Object.Description: Obtains the total number of successfully submitted requests so far.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeModuleId
Object.Description: Returns the identifier for this Component. The identifier is unique within the application. Typical modules will use the URI for their id. Web Modules will return their context-root since the web-uri may not be unique within an EAR.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeTotalCallsTriggeringReplay
Object.Description: Obtains the number of JDBC calls that triggered replay. Not all the calls affected by an outage trigger replay, because replay can be disabled for some requests.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeTotalReplayAttempts
Object.Description: Obtains the number of replay attempts. AC automatically reattempts when replay fails, so this number may exceed the number of JDBC calls that triggered replay.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeTotalProtectedCalls
Object.Description: Obtains the total number of JDBC calls executed so far that are protected by AC.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeSuccessfulReplayCount
Object.Description: Obtains the number of replays that succeeded. Successful replays mask the outages from applications.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeTotalCallsAffectedByOutages
Object.Description: Obtains the number of JDBC calls affected by outages. This includes both local calls and calls that involve roundtrip(s) to the database server.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeTotalCallsAffectedByOutagesDuringReplay
Object.Description: Obtains the number of JDBC calls affected by outages in the middle of replay. Outages may be cascaded and strike a call multiple times when replay is ongoing. AC automatically reattempts replay when this happens, unless it reaches the maximum retry limit.

Object.name: jdbcReplayStatisticsRuntimeReplayDisablingCount
Object.Description: Obtains the number of times that replay is disabled. When replay is disabled in the middle of a request, the remaining calls in that request are no longer protected by AC. In case an outage strikes one of those remaining calls, no replay will be attempted, and application simply gets an SQLRecoverableException.

Object.Description: The product name of the database that this data source is connected to.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheAccessCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of times that the statement cache was accessed.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeConnectionsTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of database connections created in this data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeDriverName
Object.Description: The product name of the JDBC driver that this data source is configured to use.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeHighestNumUnavailable
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections that were in use by applications or being tested by the system in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeDatabaseProductVersion
Object.Description: The product version of the database that this data source is connected to.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeHighestNumAvailable
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections that were idle and available to be used by an application at any time in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeWaitSecondsHighCount
Object.Description: The highest number of seconds that an application waited for a connection (the longest connection reserve wait time) from this instance of the connection pool since the connection pool was instantiated. This value is updated when a completed getConnection request takes longer to return a connection than any previous request.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of application requests concurrently waiting for a connection from this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeVersionJDBCDriver
Object.Description: The driver class name of the JDBC driver used to create database connections.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection, including those that eventually got a connection and those that did not get a connection.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeCurrCapacityHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of database connections available or in use (current capacity) in this instance of the data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeModuleId
Object.Description: Returns the identifier for this Component. The identifier is unique within the application. Typical modules will use the URI for their id. Web Modules will return their context-root since the web-uri may not be unique within an EAR.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeNumUnavailable
Object.Description: The number of connections currently in use by applications or being tested in this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheHitCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of times that statements from the cache were used.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeFailedReserveRequestCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that could not be fulfilled.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionCurrentCount
Object.Description: The number of connection requests waiting for a database connection.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeConnectionDelayTime
Object.Description: The average amount of time, in milliseconds, that it takes to create a physical connection to the database. The value is calculated as summary of all times to connect divided by the total number of connections.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionFailureTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection and eventually failed to get a connection. Waiting connection requests can fail for a variety of reasons, including waiting for longer than the ConnectionReserveTimeoutSeconds.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeNumAvailable
Object.Description: The number of database connections that are currently idle and available to be used by applications in this instance of the data source.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheAddCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of the number of statements added to the statement cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements added to the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsAverageCount
Object.Description: Average number of active connections in this instance of the data source. Active connections are connections in use by an application. This value is only valid if the resource is configured to allow shrinking.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeLeakedConnectionCount
Object.Description: The number of leaked connections. A leaked connection is a connection that was reserved from the data source but was not returned to the data source by calling close().

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeDeploymentState
Object.Description: The current deployment state of the module. A module can be in one and only one of the following states. State can be changed via deployment or administrator console. UNPREPARED. State indicating at this module is neither prepared or active. PREPARED. State indicating at this module of this application is prepared, but not active. The classes have been loaded and the module has been validated. ACTIVATED. State indicating at this module is currently active. NEW. State indicating this module has just been created and is being initialized.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheCurrentSize
Object.Description: The number of prepared and callable statements currently cached in the statement cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements in the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsCurrentCount
Object.Description: The number of connections currently in use by applications.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeEnabled
Object.Description: Indicates whether the data source is enabled or disabled: true if the data source is enabled. false if the data source is disabled.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeActiveConnectionsHighCount
Object.Description: Highest number of active database connections in this instance of the data source since the data source was instantiated. Active connections are connections in use by an application.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeCurrCapacity
Object.Description: The current count of JDBC connections in the connection pool in the data source.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeFailuresToReconnectCount
Object.Description: The number of times that the data source attempted to refresh a database connection and failed. Failures may occur when the database is unavailable or when the network connection to the database is interrupted.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeWaitingForConnectionSuccessTotal
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source that had to wait before getting a connection and eventually succeeded in getting a connection.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeDriverVersion
Object.Description: The version of the JDBC driver that this data source is configured to use.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeState
Object.Description: The current state of the data source. Possible states are: Running - the data source is enabled (deployed and not Suspended). This is the normal state of the data source. This state includes conditions when the database server is not available and the data source is created (creation retry must be enabled) or when all connections have failed connection tests (on creation, on reserve, or periodic testing). Suspended - the data source has been disabled. Shutdown - the data source is shutdown and all database connections have been closed. Overloaded - all resources in pool are in use. Unknown - the data source state is unknown.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeReserveRequestCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of requests for a connection from this data source.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheMissCount
Object.Description: The number of times that a statement request could not be satisfied with a statement from the cache.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimePrepStmtCacheDeleteCount
Object.Description: The cumulative, running count of statements discarded from the cache. Each connection in the connection pool has its own cache of statements. This number is the sum of the number of statements that were discarded from the caches for all connections in the connection pool.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeRepurposeCount
Object.Description: The number of times connections have been repurposed since the datasource was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeUnresolvedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes unsuccessfully resolved in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeResolvedAsCommittedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes successfully resolved as committed in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeCommitOutcomeRetryTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcome query retries conducted before resolving the outcome or exceeding the retry seconds in this data source since the data source was deployed.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeResolvedAsNotCommittedTotalCount
Object.Description: The cumulative total number of commit outcomes successfully resolved as not committed in this data source since the data source was deployed. This does not refer to the number of outcome query retries used to resolve the outcomes.

Object.name: jdbcUCPDataSourceRuntimeFailedRepurposeCount
Object.Description: The number of repurpose errors that have occurred since the datasource was deployed.

Table.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeTable
Table.Description: Provides methods that transition partitions from one state to another. This class is instantiated once for each partition but only on the Administration Server. Even so, you can use a partition's instance to change the state of the partition on Managed Servers as well as on the Administration Server. Detecting when Operations Complete Methods representing operations on partitions return a {@link PartitionLifeCycleTaskRuntimeMBean} object. The caller should monitor the returned instance, invoking its {@link PartitionLifeCycleTaskRuntimeMBean#isRunning()} method to detect when the operation has completed. In particular, the caller should not rely on the value returned from {@link #getState()} to indicate when an operation on a partition that is targeted to multiple servers has finished. That value will be accurate as described in detail on {@link #getState()} but can change before the operation has finished. Desired States The system tracks the desired state for each partition, which defaults to the state SHUTDOWN and substate HALTED. Whenever a lifecycle operation method is called the system not only performs the requested action on the partition but also records the resulting state as the new desired state for the partition. The system uses the desired state for a partition to bring the partition to the correct state during server restart. It can also be used when the {@link #getState()} method computes the overall state for the partition.

Object.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeEntry
Object.Description: Generated SNMP Table Entry.

Object.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Index column

Object.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

Object.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeState
Object.Description: The current overall state of the partition. The value returned is the highest state for the partition on all servers where it is targeted. As a result, the overall partition state can change (for example, to RUNNING) as soon as the operation (such as start) has finished on one server, even while the operation is still in progress elsewhere. If the partition is not currently targeted to any running server then its reported state is the desired state indicated by the most recent partition life cycle operation on the partition.

Object.name: partitionLifeCycleRuntimeSubState
Object.Description: The current substate of the partition. It is mostly useful for knowing whether the partition is completely shutdown and the administrative resource groups are not running, in which case this method returns HALTED, or if the partition is in the SHUTDOWN.BOOTED state and the administrative resource groups are running, in which case this method returns BOOTED.

Table.name: resourceGroupLifeCycleRuntimeTable
Table.Description: Provides methods that transition resource groups from one state to another. This class is instantiated once for each resource group but only on the Administration Server. Even so, you can use a resource group's instance to change the state of the resource group on Managed Servers as well as on the Administration Server. Detecting when Operations Complete Methods representing operations on resource groups return a {@link ResourceGroupLifeCycleTaskRuntimeMBean} object. The caller should monitor the returned instance, invoking its {@link ResourceGroupLifeCycleTaskRuntimeMBean#isRunning()} method to detect when the operation has completed. In particular, the caller should not rely on the value returned from {@link #getState()} to indicate when an operation on a resource group that is targeted to multiple servers has finished. That value will be accurate as described in detail on {@link #getState()} but can change before the operation has finished. Desired States The system tracks the desired state for each resource group, which defaults to the state RUNNING. Whenever a lifecycle operation method is called the system not only performs the requested action on the resource group but also records the resulting state as the new desired state for the resource group. The system uses the desired state for a resource group to bring the resource group to the correct state during server and partition start-up. The desired can also be used when the {@link #getState()} method computes the overall state for the resource group.

Object.name: resourceGroupLifeCycleRuntimeEntry

Object.name: resourceGroupLifeCycleRuntimeState
Object.Description: The current overall state of the resource group. The value returned is the highest state for the resource group on all servers where it is targeted. As a result, the overall resource group state can change (for example, to RUNNING) as soon as the operation (such as start) has finished on one server, even while the operation is still in progress elsewhere. If the resource group is not currently targeted to any running server then its reported state is the desired state indicated by the most recent resource group life cycle operation on the resource group.

Table.name: triggerRuntimeTable
Table.Description: The {@code TriggerRuntimeMBean} holds runtime state (for the current Server instance) for a Trigger that has been configured in the Resource Consumption Management policy of the current Domain Partition. The WebLogic Resource Consumption Management feature automatically initiates the configured recourse action of a Trigger when the Trigger's configured usage limits are exceeded by a Domain Partition. When a usage limit is exceeded, and the configured recourse action has been successfully executed, the Trigger is Activated. When the current resource usage by the Domain Partition falls below the Trigger's configured usage limit, the feature automatically withdraws the recourse action where possible. When the current usage is below the configured usage limit, and the configured recourse action has been successfully withdrawn, the Trigger is said to be not Activated. The MBean captures the following states for a Trigger when the current resource consumption usage by the Domain Partition exceeds or goes below the configured usage limit for the Domain Partition: Whether the Trigger is Activated (usage has exceeded the limit and the recourse action was successfully executed) or not The time when the last recourse action was executed successfully for the Trigger Whether a recourse action has been initiated in response to the resource usage by the Domain Partition exceeding the configured usage limits

Object.name: triggerRuntimeEntry
Object.Description: Generated SNMP Table Entry.

Object.name: triggerRuntimeIndex
Object.Description: Index column

Object.name: triggerRuntimeObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: triggerRuntimeName
Object.Description: The name of the Trigger, as configured in the Resource Consumption Management policy of the Domain Partition.

Object.name: triggerRuntimeActivated
Object.Description: Indicates if the Trigger is Activated.

Object.name: triggerRuntimeInitiated
Object.Description: Indicates if a recourse action has been initiated for this Trigger as a result of the current resource usage by a Domain Partition exceeding its usage limit. A new {@code RecourseActionEventVBean} is added to the array returned by {@link #getRecourseActionEventsHistory()}. The kind of recourse action initiated (for example, a new recourse action or a withdrawal of an existing recourse action) can be determined through {@link RecourseActionEventVBean#isActive()}.

Object.name: triggerRuntimeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionMaxRestartAllowed
Object.Description: Gets the value of max-restart-allowed. max-restart-allowed is defined as the maximum number of RCM initiated partition restarts allowed in the specified time interval(as specified by max-restart-allowed-interval), after which the partition will be halted upon an RCM initiated request to restart the partition.

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionMaxRestartAllowedInterval
Object.Description: Gets the value of max-restart-allowed-interval. The max-restart-allowed-interval is defined as a fixed-width, sliding-window time interval (in seconds) within which the specified number (as specified by max-restart-allowed) of RCM initiated partition restarts are permitted. A RCM initiated request to restart the partition that exceeds the given max-restart-allowed number in the given max-restart-allowed-interval will lead to the partition being halted than being restarted.

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionRestartDelay
Object.Description: The restart delay. A restart delay introduces a delay before starting the partition, as part of the RCM initiated restart action.

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionName
Object.Description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionRestartLoopProtectionEnabled
Object.Description: Checks if restart loop protection is enabled.

Object.name: restartLoopProtectionTags
Object.Description: Return all tags on this Configuration MBean

Table.name: secureModeTable
Table.Description: Controls the behavior of Secure Mode in the current WebLogic Server domain. Attributes control whether secure mode is enabled and control the validation that is performed during startup.

Object.name: secureModeEntry
Object.Description: Generated SNMP Table Entry.

Object.name: secureModeIndex
Object.Description: Index column

Object.name: secureModeObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: secureModeRestrictiveJMXPolicies
Object.Description: Returns whether restrictive policies will be used for JMX authorization. If secure mode is enabled and restrictive policies are enabled, then the default policies for JMX only allow MBean access to the standard WLS roles (Admin, Deployer, Operator, or Monitor). If changed as part of a non-dynamic activation, then the ServerSecurityRuntimeMBean.resetDefaultPolicies method should also be invoked.

Object.name: secureModeWarnOnInsecureFileSystem
Object.Description: Returns whether warnings should be logged if the File System is not secure. If secure mode is enabled and warnings are enabled, then messages will be logged for insecure file system setting.

Object.name: secureModeSecureModeEnabled
Object.Description: Returns whether the domain will run in secure mode. In secure mode, the configuration defaults are those recommended for securing a domain. The authorization policies for JNDI and MBean access are more restrictive in secure mode. In addition, WLS will validate the domain configuration and log warnings and errors for any insecure settings. Secure mode requires the domain to be in production mode.

Object.name: secureModeWarnOnJavaSecurityManager
Object.Description: Returns whether warnings should be logged if the Java Security Manager is not enabled. If secure mode is enabled and warning is enabled, then a messages will be logged if the Java Security Manager is not enabled.

Object.name: secureModeWarnOnInsecureSSL
Object.Description: Returns whether warnings should be logged if the SSL configuration is not secure. If secure mode is enabled and warnings are enabled, then messages will be logged for insecure SSL configuration settings.

Object.name: secureModeName
Object.Description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

Object.name: secureModeType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: secureModeWarnOnAuditing
Object.Description: Returns whether warnings should be logged if auditing not enabled. If secure mode is enabled and warnings are enabled, then messages will be logged if auditing is not enabled.

Object.name: secureModeWarnOnInsecureApplications
Object.Description: Returns whether warnings should be logged if applications are not secure. If secure mode is enabled and warnings are enabled, then messages will be logged for insecure application elements.

Object.name: secureModeTags
Object.Description: Return all tags on this Configuration MBean

Table.name: tLSTable
Table.Description: A TLSMBean contains SSL/TLS connection parameters and may be organized in a user-defined inheritance hierarchy and referenced by name. TODO: since 7.0.0.0 TODO: delegateBean TODO: validator TLSValidator.validateTLS

Object.name: tLSEntry
Object.Description: Generated SNMP Table Entry.

Object.name: tLSIndex
Object.Description: Index column

Object.name: tLSObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: tLSHostnameVerificationIgnored
Object.Description: Specifies whether to ignore the installed implementation of the weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier interface (when this server is acting as a client to another application server).

Object.name: tLSTwoWaySSLEnabled
Object.Description: Specifies whether to use two way SSL.

Object.name: tLSInboundCertificateValidation
Object.Description: Indicates the client certificate validation rules for inbound SSL. This attribute only applies to TLS connections using 2-way SSL.

Object.name: tLSName
Object.Description: The name of this set of TLS connection parameters.

Object.name: tLSCiphersuites
Object.Description: Specifies the cipher suites for the TLS connection. The strongest negotiated cipher suite is chosen during the SSL handshake. The set of cipher suites used by default by JSSE depends on the specific JDK version with which WebLogic Server is configured. For a list of possible values, see Cipher Suites.

Object.name: tLSOutboundCertificateValidation
Object.Description: Indicates the server certificate validation rules for outbound SSL. This attribute always applies to outbound SSL that is part of WebLogic Server (that is, an Administration Server talking to the Node Manager). It does not apply to application code in the server that is using outbound SSL unless the application code uses a weblogic.security.SSL.ServerTrustManager that is configured to use outbound SSL validation.

Object.name: tLSIdentityKeyStoreType
Object.Description: The type of the keystore. Generally, this is JKS. If using the Oracle Key Store Service, this would be KSS If empty or null, then the JDK's default keystore type (specified in java.security) is used. The identity key store type is only used if ServerMBean.KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_JAVA_STANDARD_TRUST, CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST or CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_COMMAND_LINE_TRUST.

Object.name: tLSAllowUnencryptedNullCipher
Object.Description: Specifies whether NULL ciphers are allowed for the TLS connection. When a SSL server and a SSL client try to negotiate a commonly supported Cipher, there is a chance that they may end up with nothing in common. A NullCipher is a cipher providing no encryption for the SSL message between the client and server, and it may temporarily be used in the development environment if the SSL server and client share no common cipher for some reason. This is not a standard SSL feature, some SSL provider supports this feature. The AllowUnEncryptedNullCipher flag is used to control whether the NullCipher feature is enabled or not, if true, the SSL message may be unencrypted when SSL server and client shares no common cipher. This AllowUnEncryptedNullCipher flag is only effective to SSL providers which support the NullCipher feature. Warning: this NullCipher feature should NOT be enabled for a production environment, it may leads to unencrypted SSL message By default, the AllowUnEncryptedNullCipher is false *

Object.name: tLSClientCertificateEnforced
Object.Description: Specifies whether clients must present digital certificates from a trusted certificate authority.

Object.name: tLSSSLv2HelloEnabled
Object.Description: Indicates whether SSLv2Hello is enabled in a TLS connection.

Object.name: tLSTags
Object.Description: Return all tags on this Configuration MBean

Object.name: tLSUsage
Object.Description: The declared usages of this SSL/TLS configuration.

Object.name: tLSIdentityKeyStoreFileName
Object.Description: The source of the identity keystore. For a JKS keystore, the source is the path and file name. For an Oracle Key Store Service (KSS) keystore, the source is the KSS URI. If using a JKS keystore, the keystore path name must either be absolute or relative to where the server was booted. If using a KSS keystore, the keystore URI must be of the form: kss://system/keystorename where keystorename is the name of the keystore registered in KSS. The value in this attribute is only used for a server if ServerMBean.KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_JAVA_STANDARD_TRUST, CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST or CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_COMMAND_LINE_TRUST.

Object.name: tLSMinimumTLSProtocolVersion
Object.Description: Get the minimum SSL/TLS protocol version to be used in a TLS connection. TODO: derivedDefault ((ServerTemplateMBean)(getParent())).getSSL().getMinimumTLSProtocolVersion()

Object.name: tLSHostnameVerifier
Object.Description: The name of the class that implements the weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier interface. This class verifies whether the connection to the host with the hostname from URL should be allowed. The class is used to prevent man-in-the-middle attacks. The weblogic.security.SSL.HostnameVerifier has a verify() method that WebLogic Server calls on the client during the SSL handshake.

Object.name: tLSType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: tLSTrustKeyStoreType
Object.Description: The type of the trust keystore. Generally, this is JKS. If using the Oracle Key Store Service, this would be KSS If empty or null, then the JDK's default keystore type (specified in java.security) is used. The trust key store type is only used if ServerMBean.KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST.

Object.name: tLSTrustKeyStoreFileName
Object.Description: The source of the trust keystore. For a JKS keystore, the source is the path and file name. For an Oracle Key Store Service (KSS) keystore, the source is the KSS URI. If using a JKS keystore, the keystore path name must either be absolute or relative to where the server was booted. If using a KSS keystore, the keystore URI must be of the form: kss://system/keystorename where keystorename is the name of the keystore registered in KSS. The value in this attribute is only used for a server if ServerMBean.KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST.

Object.name: tLSIdentityPrivateKeyAlias
Object.Description: The alias of the private key representing the identity for the associated connection. The alias refers to a private key in {@link #getIdentityKeyStoreFileName()}

Table.name: http2ConfigTable
Table.Description: The local setting of an HTTP/2 connection on a web server.

Object.name: http2ConfigEntry
Object.Description: Generated SNMP Table Entry.

Object.name: http2ConfigIndex
Object.Description: Index column

Object.name: http2ConfigObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: http2ConfigMaxHeaderListSize
Object.Description: The maximum size of header list that the server is prepared to accept, in octets. The value is based on the uncompressed size of header fields, including the length of the name and value in octets plus an overhead of 32 octets for each header field.

Object.name: http2ConfigInitialWindowSize
Object.Description: The server's initial window size (in octets) for stream-level flow control. This setting affects the window size of all streams.

Object.name: http2ConfigName
Object.Description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

Object.name: http2ConfigType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: http2ConfigMaxConcurrentStreams
Object.Description: The maximum number of concurrent streams that the server will allow. This limit is directional: it applies to the number of streams that the server permits the receiver to create.

Object.name: http2ConfigHeaderTableSize
Object.Description: The server's maximum size of the header compression table used to decode header blocks, in octets.

Object.name: http2ConfigMaxFrameSize
Object.Description: The size of the largest frame payload that the server is willing to receive, in octets.

Object.name: http2ConfigTags
Object.Description: Return all tags on this Configuration MBean

Table.name: jmsSystemResourceTable
Table.Description: This bean defines a system-level JMS resource. It links a separate descriptor that specifies the definition.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceEntry
Object.Description: Generated SNMP Table Entry.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceIndex
Object.Description: Index column

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceObjectName
Object.Description: ObjectName column

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceDescriptorFileName
Object.Description: The name of the file that contains the module configuration. By default the file resides in the DOMAIN_DIR/config/jms directory. The module file derives its name from the bean name using the following pattern: <beanName>.xml Note that this is a read-only property that can only be set when the bean is created.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceCompatibilityName
Object.Description: This is only set for beans created as a result of conversion from an 8.1 application configured using ApplicationMBean and ComponentMBean. Standalone modules in 8.1 have both an ApplicationMBean name and ComponentMBean name. This attribute stores the name of the latter, to be used when the server creates the transient ComponentMBean for backward compatibility.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceName
Object.Description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceModuleType
Object.Description: The values match those defined by jsr88. This attribute may move to another MBean.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceType
Object.Description: Returns the type of the MBean.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceDeploymentPrincipalName
Object.Description: A string value that indicates the principal that should be used when deploying the file or archive during startup and shutdown. This principal will be used to set the current subject when calling out into application code for interfaces such as ApplicationLifecycleListener. If no principal name is specified, then the anonymous principal will be used.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceDeploymentOrder
Object.Description: An integer value that indicates when this unit is deployed, relative to other deployable units on a server, during startup. Units with lower values are deployed before those with higher values.

Object.name: jmsSystemResourceTags
Object.Description: Return all tags on this Configuration MBean
